2. Local Growth with Claude CLI
To develop each repo separately while maintaining the monorepo structure, use Claude CLI (claude) with localized context files.

Isolated Context: Place a CLAUDE.md file in each sub-directory (e.g., apps/powerstarter/CLAUDE.md).
Root CLAUDE.md: Define monorepo build commands (e.g., pnpm build).
App-specific CLAUDE.md: Define local test commands and architectural patterns for just that app.

The "Claude Workflow":
cd apps/powerstarter && claude: Start a session focused only on the portfolio logic.
Use /plan to map out the API handler without touching the Unity code.
Run /commit within the sub-directory. Claude CLI will intelligently draft a commit message based on local changes.
Global Integration: Periodically run claude from the root directory to perform cross-repo audits or update the shared Prisma schema.

3. Seamless Monorepo Architecture
To make the repos "talk" to each other without friction, follow these structural rules:
Component	Responsibility	Shared Link
packages/db	Holds schema.prisma and exports a Singleton Prisma Client.	All apps import from @repo/db.
packages/ui	Shared design tokens (colors, icons) based on RootPlanner states.	Used by Powerstarter web.
apps/powerstarter	Hosts the API Handlers that Unity also calls.	Acts as the central gateway.

Procedural Implementation Steps
Initialize the Shared DB
In packages/db, define your schema with provider = "prisma-client-js" and a custom output path so all apps can find the generated types easily.
Build the Sync API
Create a route in Next.js that accepts POST requests from the RootPlanner. Use a Zod schema (shared in packages/validation) to ensure the BMS data is valid before it hits the database.
Unity Integration
Configure Unity to call the powerstarter API endpoints using UnityWebRequest. Since the logic is shared in the monorepo, you can export your TypeScript types as a JSON reference for Unity's C# classes to match.

