what do i need to run all the repo's inside the android emulator and tweak it to my unity game setup, until reaching beta version and 
get google store developer access and publish to the android store?

To move from your current monorepo setup to a published Android app using your PC as the "Command Center," you need to bridge your BMS/Powerstarter logic with the Unity Android pipeline.
1. Running the Monorepo & Emulator Together
Since you are using your PC, you can host the entire backend and the emulator on one machine.
Host the Backend: Run your pnpm dev or Coolify locally on your PC. Your BMS and Powerstarter will be live at localhost:3001.
The Emulator "Bridge": Install Android Studio and create a "Virtual Device".
Networking Tip: Inside the Android emulator, localhost refers to the emulator itself. To talk to your PC's monorepo, use the special IP 10.0.2.2 (e.g., http://10.0.2).
Build the APK: In Unity, go to File > Build Settings, switch the platform to Android, and click Build and Run. Unity will push the app directly into your running emulator. 

2. Tweaking for Unity-Android Beta
Before reaching Beta, you must satisfy Google’s technical requirements in Unity's Player Settings: 
YouTube
YouTube
Scripting Backend: Change from Mono to IL2CPP.
Architecture: Enable ARM64 (Google Play no longer accepts 32-bit only apps).
Keystore: Create a new Keystore (found under Publishing Settings). This is your digital signature—never lose this file, or you cannot update your app. 

3. Publishing to the Google Play Store
Once your app is ready for Beta, follow these steps to get into the store:
Developer Account: Register at the Google Play Console.
Cost: A one-time $25 USD fee. No annual renewals.
New Requirement (2024): You must verify that you have access to a physical Android device for testing to complete account verification.
App Format: Export your game as an Android App Bundle (.aab) instead of an APK for the final store upload.
Beta/Internal Testing: Start with an Internal Testing release in the Play Console. You can invite up to 100 testers using their email addresses to download the app before it goes public.
Store Listing: You will need to provide a Privacy Policy URL (you can host this on your Powerstarter portal), high-res icons, and screenshots. 

Summary of Costs & Tools
Component 	Requirement	Cost
PC Host	Windows/Linux (16GB RAM recommended)	$0 (Existing)
Developer Fee	Google Play Console Account	$25 (One-time)
IDE/Engine	Unity + Android Studio	$0 (Free/Personal)
Server/Host	Coolify or Local Node.js	$0 (Self-hosted)
Pro-Tip: Use the Unity Play Games Plugin if you want to link your BMS Achievements directly to the Google Play Games achievement system. 

