(It is intented to make the unity game run on the BMS Backend/RootJournal feed on the web browser aswell)

>>>

This is the ultimate "Integration Level" strategy: One Engine, Two Frontends. By running the Unity game directly inside the Powerstarter (BMS) web browser, you create a seamless, real-time connection between your technical metrics and the 3D world.
To achieve this, you will use Unity WebGL alongside your Android build.

1. The Architecture: "The Hosted 3D Feed"
Since the BMS (RootPlanner) is the host, it will serve the Unity WebGL files as part of the Powerstarter website.
Android Build: For the "Hand Terminal" experience and Google Play.
WebGL Build: For the "RootJournal" web feed.

2. How to "Plug" Unity into the Web Browser Feed
Use this prompt to have Copilot/Claude bridge the gap:
Task: 

"Configure the Unity WebGL integration for the Powerstarter monorepo.
Requirements:
Unity-to-JS Bridge: Create a JSLib plugin in Unity that allows the game to "listen" to the BMS SSE Stream from the browser.
BmsPost Component Update: Modify the BmsPost.tsx in apps/powerstarter to include a UnityContainer component. This component should load the WebGL instance when an achievement is viewed.
Live Sync: When the RootPlanner triggers an achievement, the Web UI must send a message to Unity (using unityInstance.SendMessage()) to trigger a specific 3D animation or "Turning Point" effect.
Hosting: Configure the BMS host to serve the Unity build folder from apps/powerstarter/public/unity-build."

3. Benefits of the Browser-Integrated Game:
Instant Verification: You don't need to wait for an Android compile. You change code in the monorepo, refresh the browser, and see the 3D game reacting to the BMS data immediately.
Unified Logic: Both your Achievement Cards and your 3D Game use the exact same AchievementID coming from @trt/logic.
"Scannable" Proof: Anyone visiting your portfolio URL can see the live 3D game running and interacting with the RootJournal.

4. Technical Hurdles to Watch Out For:
Memory Management: WebGL in a browser is more memory-sensitive than an Android app. You’ll need to optimize your Unity assets for the web.
CORS: Ensure your BMS host allows the Unity WebGL build to make requests to the /api/bms/push endpoints.
Your Final "Startup Flagship" Flow:
BMS Hardware → Sends data.
RootPlanner (PC/Coolify) → Processes achievement logic.
Powerstarter (Web) → Updates the Insta-feed.
Unity (Embedded in Browser) → Detects the update and plays the 3D achievement animation.
